cal)\n- excellent computer skills (technical)\n- weak memory for numbers (weakness)\n- makes nasty remarks about colleagues (teamwork/communication negative)\n- can be grumpy (attitude)\n- can be uncooperative (teamwork negative)\n\nC:\n- can make correct decisions quickly (judgment)\n- difficulty communicating ideas (teamwork weakness)\n- regarded as egocentric (attitude)\n- not very willing to further his education (professional development)\n- 100% reliable (reliability)\n- creates a positive atmosphere with his crew (teamwork positive)\n- puts concern for others above everything (teamwork positive)\n- (also earlier mention: excellent attention skills? Actually not in list but maybe from earlier? Not needed)\n\nD:\n- responds to unexpected events adequately (judgment)\n- can concentrate very well (cognitive)\n- solves problems extremely well (technical/cognitive)\n- takes responsibility seriously (reliability)\n- regarded as arrogant (attitude)\n- relatively weak leadership skills (leadership)\n- hot temper (attitude)\n- know-it-all (attitude)\n\nNow evaluate for long-distance pilot: need reliability, decision-making, stress handling, teamwork, communication, professional development.\n\nWe weigh strengths vs weaknesses.\n\nCandidate A: strong anticipation, complex connections, spatial vision, leadership. Weaknesses: unorganized, poor at criticism, show-off, not open to new ideas. Unorganized could affect long flights. Not open to new ideas may hinder learning. Leadership good.\n\nCandidate B: conscientious, stress handling, weather assessment, computer skills. Weaknesses: nasty remarks, uncooperative, grumpy, weak memory for numbers (important for calculations). Teamwork issues.\n\nCandidate C: 100% reliable, quick correct decisions, creates positive atmosphere, concern for others, but difficulty communicating, egocentric, not willing to further education. Positive crew atmosphere is strong for teamwork. Communication difficulty could be problematic for cockpit 